explanation:
Agent A is correct. In the HEADERS_SENDING case the local is declared as
  struct MHD_Response *const resp = connection->rp.response;
which makes the pointer itself const (cannot be reseated) but not the pointed-to object. All uses of resp in that block are read-only (assertions and passing fields to send functions); the code does not write via resp. Therefore the pointed-to type can be const-qualified and should be to comply with MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 ("A pointer should point to a const-qualified type whenever possible"). A suitable fix is e.g.:
  const struct MHD_Response * const resp = connection->rp.response;
or at minimum
  const struct MHD_Response * resp = connection->rp.response;
(choose the form consistent with the project's const-qualification conventions). Note: if any of the called functions or later code require a non-const pointer or the code intends to modify the response via this pointer, adding const would be inappropriate; in the shown block that does not occur, so adding const is safe and recommended.
